<br>
I believe that people can use these methods to connect to their inner spiritual nature.  IMO the reason people think these methods are evil is because their preacher told them so.  What better way to get people to flock to your religion than to convince them that every method of spirituality connection they pursue is wrong?  People believe you need a god to be spiritual because that is what they are told.  If someone chooses God as their spiritual path, then I can totally respect that.  I was there once myself.  But to scare someone into believing in God by squashing all other ideas is plain wrong.  I feel spiritual in the sense that I can connect with my inner emotions and the emotions of others.  I feel part of something bigger in the sense that I know everything I say or do will have an effect on someone else's life.  I can also appreciate the beauty of the Rocky Mountains without attributing that beauty to a deity.  I find beauty in science and the natural order of things.  I am in awe of everything from the snowcapped mountains to my son's little fingers and toes.  I don't need to fear a deity to feel this way.  If there is a God, then maybe he would just be happy with the fact that I was capable of appreciating the beautiful gifts he gave us without having to rely on other human beings to fill my head with reasons that I should be too scared to not appreciate these things.  I have discovered the beauty of life and connection to others without the help of any religion.  Everyone has their own path, and the path I chose just happened to be nonreligious.<br>
<br>
